âœ… HashMap vs Hashtable in Java
| Feature              | **HashMap**                                                                         | **Hashtable**                                       |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| **Thread Safety**    | âŒ Not thread-safe (needs manual sync)                                               | âœ… Thread-safe (methods are synchronized)            |
| **Performance**      | âœ… Faster (no synchronization overhead)                                              | âŒ Slower due to method-level synchronization        |
| **Null keys/values** | âœ… Allows **1 null key** and **multiple null values**                                | âŒ **Does not allow** any null key or value          |
| **Introduced in**    | Java 1.2 (part of the Collections Framework)                                        | Java 1.0 (legacy class)                             |
| **Use case**         | For **single-threaded** or manually synchronized apps                               | For **legacy multithreaded** applications           |
| **Iterator type**    | **Fail-fast** â€“ throws `ConcurrentModificationException` on concurrent modification | **Fail-safe** â€“ no exception (but weak consistency) |
| **Extends**          | `AbstractMap`                                                                       | `Dictionary` (old abstract class)                   |


ğŸ” Example:
âœ… HashMap:
Map<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put(null, "value");       // âœ” Allowed
map.put("key", null);         // âœ” Allowed

âœ… Correct version:
"Insertion order can be preserved by using LinkedHashMap, which is a subclass of HashMap."

ğŸ§  Explanation:
HashMap itself does not maintain insertion order.

But its subclass LinkedHashMap adds a doubly linked list to maintain the order in which entries were inserted.

So if you want the features of a HashMap + insertion order, use LinkedHashMap.


âŒ Hashtable:
Map<String, String> table = new Hashtable<>();
table.put(null, "value");     // âŒ Throws NullPointerException

ğŸ” When to use what?
| Scenario                              | Recommendation                                 |
| ------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Multithreaded application             | âœ… Use `ConcurrentHashMap` instead of Hashtable |
| General-purpose use (single-threaded) | âœ… Use `HashMap`                                |
| Legacy code compatibility             | Use `Hashtable` only if required               |


âœ… Summary:
Use HashMap in most modern Java applications.

Avoid Hashtable unless you're maintaining very old code.

For thread safety, use ConcurrentHashMap instead â€” it's more efficient and modern.